1
00:00:04,861 --> 00:00:06,362
OK.

2
00:00:06,362 --> 00:00:07,402
Cool.

3
00:00:07,402 --> 00:00:09,724
Great to see that you came here today.

4
00:00:09,724 --> 00:00:12,145
It was the toughest possible competition, Diablo 3

5
00:00:12,145 --> 00:00:15,887
post-mortem in the other hall, and Friday afternoon.

6
00:00:15,887 --> 00:00:18,709
So thank you for showing up.

7
00:00:18,709 --> 00:00:21,050
My name is Fred, and I have the privilege

8
00:00:21,050 --> 00:00:24,973
of being the CEO and president of Paradox Interactive, which

9
00:00:24,973 --> 00:00:28,335
has been growing really rapidly in the past two, three years.

10
00:00:29,590 --> 00:00:31,771
And you might know us from titles like Crusader Kings,

11
00:00:31,771 --> 00:00:34,852
Europa, and Versales, Cities Skylines, Magicka.

12
00:00:34,852 --> 00:00:39,533
And today I'm going to talk about business models.

13
00:00:39,533 --> 00:00:40,914
And I think that in our industry,

14
00:00:40,914 --> 00:00:42,935
we don't talk about business enough.

15
00:00:42,935 --> 00:00:45,695
So I used to work more with games 10 years ago,

16
00:00:45,695 --> 00:00:47,356
when the studio was small.

17
00:00:47,356 --> 00:00:50,397
And I was kind of, even if I was the sales and marketing

18
00:00:50,397 --> 00:00:53,698
guy all the time, I still was a part of the games development

19
00:00:53,698 --> 00:00:54,238
team as well.

20
00:00:54,238 --> 00:00:57,239
But the more I moved out of the games development team,

21
00:00:57,239 --> 00:00:59,200
the better games we started creating.

22
00:01:00,512 --> 00:01:04,214
And even more so, the better business we started making,

23
00:01:04,214 --> 00:01:06,716
because I could focus on what I do best.

24
00:01:06,716 --> 00:01:09,558
So my goal of today is to actually make

25
00:01:09,558 --> 00:01:12,620
more game developers talk about business and business models.

26
00:01:12,620 --> 00:01:18,905
And this is one of my favorite all-time quotes

27
00:01:18,905 --> 00:01:20,226
from Warren Buffett.

28
00:01:21,102 --> 00:01:23,763
Price is what you pay and value is what you get.

29
00:01:23,763 --> 00:01:26,144
Because all markets are basically imperfect,

30
00:01:26,144 --> 00:01:29,306
because we value things totally different.

31
00:01:29,306 --> 00:01:32,107
So someone might value Europa Universalis

32
00:01:32,107 --> 00:01:36,088
at the price of $2,000, because they're putting 4,000 hours

33
00:01:36,088 --> 00:01:36,849
into the game.

34
00:01:36,849 --> 00:01:39,710
Some other people might value this at $1 or $2,

35
00:01:39,710 --> 00:01:42,691
because they'd like just to see what it is,

36
00:01:42,691 --> 00:01:46,493
play it for a little while, and then let it be and have it

37
00:01:46,493 --> 00:01:47,533
in their Steam catalog.

38
00:01:48,081 --> 00:01:54,603
Now, price discrimination doesn't allow us to do that, to charge exactly what people

39
00:01:54,603 --> 00:01:56,704
want to pay for something.

40
00:01:56,704 --> 00:02:00,225
So all markets are in some ways imperfect.

41
00:02:00,225 --> 00:02:04,287
But once you move into a digital world like we're in, most of us in here, we move away

42
00:02:04,287 --> 00:02:08,749
from retail boxes, we can start experimenting much more, both on the pricing side and on

43
00:02:08,749 --> 00:02:09,889
the business model side.

44
00:02:11,710 --> 00:02:16,096
So I'm going to show you some models that we use at Paradox, how we start with a game,

45
00:02:16,096 --> 00:02:20,601
how we integrate the business model, and how we integrate people around the business model,

46
00:02:20,601 --> 00:02:22,704
the value creators that we're working with.

47
00:02:22,704 --> 00:02:27,129
So we are not the only ones making value for our own titles, for our own games.

48
00:02:30,067 --> 00:02:35,232
And starting just by, like, I'm going to use a few words that I come back to here,

49
00:02:35,232 --> 00:02:38,054
and maybe some of you are not familiar with these words,

50
00:02:38,054 --> 00:02:40,276
but business model.

51
00:02:40,276 --> 00:02:42,358
Once you hear that, what is a business model?

52
00:02:42,358 --> 00:02:46,782
Well, it's basically how do you make money?

53
00:02:46,782 --> 00:02:49,805
So even if you don't talk about business models,

54
00:02:49,805 --> 00:02:51,846
you will have a business model in your company

55
00:02:51,846 --> 00:02:53,508
if you have revenue coming into the company.

56
00:02:55,103 --> 00:02:57,406
The second one is value proposition.

57
00:02:57,406 --> 00:03:00,549
And value proposition is the promised value

58
00:03:00,549 --> 00:03:03,772
that you're supposed to deliver to a customer who's

59
00:03:03,772 --> 00:03:05,173
going to use your product.

60
00:03:05,173 --> 00:03:08,637
And that has also been approved by said customer.

61
00:03:08,637 --> 00:03:13,301
And the value chain is everyone who

62
00:03:13,301 --> 00:03:16,164
creates value to put together the value proposition.

63
00:03:16,164 --> 00:03:18,807
Are you with me?

64
00:03:18,807 --> 00:03:19,067
Cool.

65
00:03:20,095 --> 00:03:21,956
This is all CEO art as well.

66
00:03:21,956 --> 00:03:22,797
Did I mention that?

67
00:03:22,797 --> 00:03:27,940
I made this presentation myself, so it might look a bit so-so.

68
00:03:27,940 --> 00:03:30,302
So when you build value chains and business model,

69
00:03:30,302 --> 00:03:31,442
you have to start somewhere.

70
00:03:31,442 --> 00:03:34,184
You have to start like, where do we start talking about this?

71
00:03:34,184 --> 00:03:35,905
Where do we start building our business models?

72
00:03:35,905 --> 00:03:39,327
And the first thing you should talk about at your studio

73
00:03:39,327 --> 00:03:43,090
or whatever business you run is, how do we want to make money?

74
00:03:45,157 --> 00:03:50,259
Not only what are we charging for the products, but philosophically, how do we want to make money?

75
00:03:50,259 --> 00:03:52,440
How do we want to sell our products to our customers?

76
00:03:52,440 --> 00:03:57,983
Like, at Paradox, we've said that we do not want to monetize frustration.

77
00:03:57,983 --> 00:04:00,284
That's one of our key pillars in our business model.

78
00:04:00,284 --> 00:04:07,828
Meaning that, if your character dies in Crusader Kings 2, you cannot buy him back for a dollar.

79
00:04:09,337 --> 00:04:12,782
That would be a bit so-so, because people would be frustrated, right?

80
00:04:12,782 --> 00:04:14,284
And then you can pay your way out of that.

81
00:04:14,284 --> 00:04:16,628
We don't think that's a good way to approach a brand.

82
00:04:16,628 --> 00:04:18,991
So we want people to pay for our games

83
00:04:18,991 --> 00:04:23,738
when they're at, like, really stoked to play something new.

84
00:04:27,028 --> 00:04:29,069
Also, getting the team excited about the numbers.

85
00:04:29,069 --> 00:04:30,450
Start talking about the numbers.

86
00:04:30,450 --> 00:04:32,352
Saying, what are our goals with this?

87
00:04:32,352 --> 00:04:35,534
Not only on the money side, it could be other key performance

88
00:04:35,534 --> 00:04:36,976
indicators as well.

89
00:04:36,976 --> 00:04:39,377
But just get the team excited about the numbers.

90
00:04:39,377 --> 00:04:43,060
Because once we started to get our development team more

91
00:04:43,060 --> 00:04:46,023
excited about the numbers, we started to make better games.

92
00:04:46,023 --> 00:04:47,083
Fact.

93
00:04:47,083 --> 00:04:51,207
You also need a customer approval.

94
00:04:52,262 --> 00:04:54,563
I'm going to get back to this as well, because the customers

95
00:04:54,563 --> 00:04:56,883
are a part of everything you do all the time.

96
00:04:56,883 --> 00:04:58,184
They will have opinions about it.

97
00:04:58,184 --> 00:05:00,685
They will tell you when they think you make mistakes.

98
00:05:00,685 --> 00:05:04,366
And they will turn on you if you make enough mistakes

99
00:05:04,366 --> 00:05:05,746
in a short while.

100
00:05:05,746 --> 00:05:10,307
Also, get the customer engagement

101
00:05:10,307 --> 00:05:12,668
so that they will drive the process further.

102
00:05:12,668 --> 00:05:14,588
Not only approval, but asking like,

103
00:05:14,588 --> 00:05:17,369
how can you help us evolve our business models

104
00:05:17,369 --> 00:05:19,130
and our value proposition, and both.

105
00:05:22,596 --> 00:05:24,778
So intro, we start with the games, right?

106
00:05:24,778 --> 00:05:27,420
Because everyone here, how many are game developers in here?

107
00:05:27,420 --> 00:05:27,820
Hands up.

108
00:05:27,820 --> 00:05:29,482
Most of you.

109
00:05:29,482 --> 00:05:32,945
And the people who work in sales and marketing, anyone?

110
00:05:32,945 --> 00:05:34,886
Few as well.

111
00:05:34,886 --> 00:05:35,226
Any media?

112
00:05:35,226 --> 00:05:38,329
No media, that's good.

113
00:05:38,329 --> 00:05:40,211
Then I can speak freely, that's very good.

114
00:05:40,211 --> 00:05:40,751
Good, we start with the game.

115
00:05:40,751 --> 00:05:44,434
So when we look at a new game, we

116
00:05:44,434 --> 00:05:47,537
look at something from the internal studio,

117
00:05:47,537 --> 00:05:49,138
or we look to publish something.

118
00:05:49,138 --> 00:05:50,399
We talk about three things.

119
00:05:51,912 --> 00:05:55,633
And the first thing is, do we have the passion to do this game?

120
00:05:55,633 --> 00:06:00,195
Do we think that we have the people who will walk 10 extra miles

121
00:06:00,195 --> 00:06:01,335
to make this game really good?

122
00:06:01,335 --> 00:06:06,737
The second one is market.

123
00:06:06,737 --> 00:06:10,058
Is there actually a market for a game like this?

124
00:06:10,058 --> 00:06:12,139
If there's an established competitor, for example,

125
00:06:12,139 --> 00:06:14,420
you can always look at the competitor,

126
00:06:14,420 --> 00:06:15,820
but if you're creating something new,

127
00:06:15,820 --> 00:06:18,902
you have to kind of second-guess if there's a market or not,

128
00:06:18,902 --> 00:06:20,222
trying to quantify it.

129
00:06:20,222 --> 00:06:20,622
But still...

130
00:06:22,982 --> 00:06:24,343
And the third one, obviously, is skill.

131
00:06:24,343 --> 00:06:27,063
Do we have the skills to do this?

132
00:06:27,063 --> 00:06:29,704
Passion is not enough to actually complete

133
00:06:29,704 --> 00:06:31,284
the project that's going to be world class.

134
00:06:31,284 --> 00:06:32,945
So you need the skills to do it.

135
00:06:32,945 --> 00:06:34,545
Do we have the resources to actually pull through?

136
00:06:34,545 --> 00:06:38,546
The resources are not only on the development side.

137
00:06:38,546 --> 00:06:40,567
It's also on the sales and marketing side.

138
00:06:40,567 --> 00:06:42,307
We've had numerous discussions.

139
00:06:42,307 --> 00:06:44,588
This is 10 years ago.

140
00:06:44,588 --> 00:06:47,929
But still, whether a good game sells itself.

141
00:06:47,929 --> 00:06:51,410
How many in here would say a good game sells itself?

142
00:06:52,243 --> 00:06:53,384
Anyone?

143
00:06:53,384 --> 00:06:55,205
Yeah, a few really brave souls.

144
00:06:55,205 --> 00:06:58,626
That's good.

145
00:06:58,626 --> 00:07:01,587
So let's look at our funnel.

146
00:07:01,587 --> 00:07:04,148
How tight is the Paradox funnel?

147
00:07:04,148 --> 00:07:07,289
When we look at new games and new time, how critical are we

148
00:07:07,289 --> 00:07:10,550
about new concepts coming into Paradox, or old concepts, for

149
00:07:10,550 --> 00:07:12,031
that matter?

150
00:07:12,031 --> 00:07:15,612
I once was pitched a game called Fish Tetris, which was

151
00:07:15,612 --> 00:07:17,373
you should match fishes against each

152
00:07:17,373 --> 00:07:19,254
other to remove them.

153
00:07:19,254 --> 00:07:21,555
That's one of the most terrible pitches I've ever seen.

154
00:07:22,939 --> 00:07:27,400
And that's one, probably of the 400 in here, 401, specifically,

155
00:07:27,400 --> 00:07:28,421
something like fish tetras.

156
00:07:28,421 --> 00:07:32,322
Those were the pitches received total in 2015

157
00:07:32,322 --> 00:07:34,903
to Paradox Interactive, 401 pitches in total,

158
00:07:34,903 --> 00:07:38,124
which is more than one pitch a day.

159
00:07:38,124 --> 00:07:43,765
And of the 400 pitches, 20 went to the Green Light Committee

160
00:07:43,765 --> 00:07:45,046
for further research.

161
00:07:46,102 --> 00:07:50,225
And the games that we are actually signing for further,

162
00:07:50,225 --> 00:07:53,368
like up until prototype, is between one and three.

163
00:07:53,368 --> 00:07:55,730
Probably all three of them.

164
00:07:55,730 --> 00:07:57,271
But at least one of those projects

165
00:07:57,271 --> 00:07:59,653
will be closed before it reaches prototype stage.

166
00:07:59,653 --> 00:08:02,195
That's how tight the funnel is.

167
00:08:02,195 --> 00:08:05,678
And then you go over to what are the reasons for declining

168
00:08:05,678 --> 00:08:07,579
so many games.

169
00:08:07,579 --> 00:08:10,021
First of all, there are genre issues.

170
00:08:10,021 --> 00:08:12,663
We have decided what makes a Paradox game.

171
00:08:12,663 --> 00:08:15,045
And I'm going to come back to that with even more C-E-O-R.

172
00:08:17,020 --> 00:08:18,902
We stand for something.

173
00:08:18,902 --> 00:08:22,526
And if the game doesn't stand for the same thing as we do,

174
00:08:22,526 --> 00:08:24,188
we can't sign the game, no matter how good it is.

175
00:08:24,188 --> 00:08:27,551
Then you have pillar issues, which

176
00:08:27,551 --> 00:08:28,932
is very, very game-specific.

177
00:08:28,932 --> 00:08:32,015
And then you have, of course, development issues as well.

178
00:08:32,015 --> 00:08:34,177
Is the developer not the right developer?

179
00:08:34,177 --> 00:08:36,940
We don't think they can actually make this game happen.

180
00:08:36,940 --> 00:08:40,143
Just to give you a glance on how we work.

181
00:08:42,408 --> 00:08:44,789
The first thing we do when we look at a new game

182
00:08:44,789 --> 00:08:47,790
or look at a new project overall is setting the vision.

183
00:08:47,790 --> 00:08:49,770
And a vision is really important

184
00:08:49,770 --> 00:08:51,091
because when you look at the wall

185
00:08:51,091 --> 00:08:54,872
and you see the vision every day, you can unite your team.

186
00:08:54,872 --> 00:08:57,353
There are a couple of good visions out there.

187
00:08:57,353 --> 00:09:01,294
I mean, we use for our upcoming space game Stellaris.

188
00:09:01,294 --> 00:09:04,675
The galaxy is vast and full of wonders.

189
00:09:04,675 --> 00:09:06,476
So what does that say when you look at it?

190
00:09:06,476 --> 00:09:09,657
It says that it's kind of different from our other games.

191
00:09:10,285 --> 00:09:14,547
because Europa Universalis is...

192
00:09:14,547 --> 00:09:16,087
there is no exploration in that game.

193
00:09:16,087 --> 00:09:20,288
So the implicated thing in Solaris is that it starts with exploration.

194
00:09:20,288 --> 00:09:24,670
For example, they can interpret this in many different ways, of course,

195
00:09:24,670 --> 00:09:27,250
but you can unite the team behind the vision.

196
00:09:27,250 --> 00:09:30,692
My absolute favorite vision, I think it's the vision at least,

197
00:09:30,692 --> 00:09:33,152
that's what I heard, is for Gears of War.

198
00:09:33,152 --> 00:09:36,793
And, very easy to understand,

199
00:09:36,793 --> 00:09:38,994
Marcus Fenix is a badass.

200
00:09:40,255 --> 00:09:41,416
That's good.

201
00:09:41,416 --> 00:09:42,636
Why is that a good vision?

202
00:09:42,636 --> 00:09:45,217
Because when you look at Marcus Fenix,

203
00:09:45,217 --> 00:09:46,458
you see he's a badass.

204
00:09:46,458 --> 00:09:49,839
The artists who work with Marcus Fenix

205
00:09:49,839 --> 00:09:52,740
knows that he should be painted as a badass.

206
00:09:52,740 --> 00:09:53,841
He doesn't open doors.

207
00:09:53,841 --> 00:09:56,002
He kicks doors in because he's a badass.

208
00:09:56,002 --> 00:09:57,803
So everything in the game design,

209
00:09:57,803 --> 00:09:58,843
everything in the art,

210
00:09:58,843 --> 00:10:00,584
everything in the level design

211
00:10:00,584 --> 00:10:02,344
implies that he's a badass.

212
00:10:02,344 --> 00:10:03,805
Everyone can get behind that.

213
00:10:03,805 --> 00:10:07,647
So why do you actually set this vision,

214
00:10:07,647 --> 00:10:08,987
and why is it so important?

215
00:10:10,063 --> 00:10:13,026
You help the team find the direction of what they do.

216
00:10:13,026 --> 00:10:16,088
It's really easy to communicate to your fans.

217
00:10:16,088 --> 00:10:19,311
It's part of your marketing plan as well.

218
00:10:19,311 --> 00:10:22,354
You can find angles in the marketing that actually

219
00:10:22,354 --> 00:10:26,598
explains the vision and even deepens it even more.

220
00:10:26,598 --> 00:10:28,980
And of course, you identify the priorities as well.

221
00:10:28,980 --> 00:10:32,583
You can talk about what's the most badass of these two

222
00:10:32,583 --> 00:10:33,264
choices that we have.

223
00:10:36,084 --> 00:10:37,285
And how do you set this?

224
00:10:37,285 --> 00:10:39,327
A vision is not easily completed.

225
00:10:39,327 --> 00:10:41,189
The worst visions you can ever have

226
00:10:41,189 --> 00:10:44,371
is this is going to be the best strategy game ever.

227
00:10:44,371 --> 00:10:47,794
No one has a clue what they're supposed to do.

228
00:10:47,794 --> 00:10:49,436
It doesn't set an angle.

229
00:10:49,436 --> 00:10:50,997
It doesn't set a direction.

230
00:10:50,997 --> 00:10:53,560
It just says it's going to be really good once it's finished.

231
00:10:53,560 --> 00:10:56,642
Or the best World War II game ever made.

232
00:10:56,642 --> 00:10:58,444
It's a terrible vision.

233
00:10:58,444 --> 00:10:59,064
Terrible.

234
00:10:59,064 --> 00:11:01,667
Could be a statement, or it could

235
00:11:01,667 --> 00:11:03,608
be a general feeling that makes up your visions.

236
00:11:05,304 --> 00:11:08,306
And the people making it should be everyone involved

237
00:11:08,306 --> 00:11:08,566
in the team.

238
00:11:08,566 --> 00:11:09,807
And I'll get back to that as well,

239
00:11:09,807 --> 00:11:12,929
why it's so important to mix and match teams

240
00:11:12,929 --> 00:11:16,992
between not only development, but also sales, marketing,

241
00:11:16,992 --> 00:11:18,232
and all other parts of the company.

242
00:11:18,232 --> 00:11:19,053
Dreaming big is the next step.

243
00:11:19,053 --> 00:11:23,235
We feel that, OK, we're doing something new here,

244
00:11:23,235 --> 00:11:27,318
something new, cool, that people should be excited about.

245
00:11:27,318 --> 00:11:30,160
So we'll dream 18 to 24 months ahead.

246
00:11:30,160 --> 00:11:31,921
The game is already out there.

247
00:11:31,921 --> 00:11:32,661
It's a big success.

248
00:11:32,661 --> 00:11:34,603
Everyone wants to play it.

249
00:11:35,162 --> 00:11:37,943
So who is playing this game?

250
00:11:37,943 --> 00:11:41,884
If it was a book written on this game, who would write the book

251
00:11:41,884 --> 00:11:43,905
and what type of book would that be?

252
00:11:43,905 --> 00:11:44,965
Who would be the author?

253
00:11:44,965 --> 00:11:49,906
Would it be Stephen King or would it be Ernest Hemingway?

254
00:11:49,906 --> 00:11:51,247
Wear it.

255
00:11:51,247 --> 00:11:53,587
Like, how do you cosplay this game?

256
00:11:53,587 --> 00:11:55,228
How do you make the game have a soul?

