00:42:45,645 --> 00:42:47,609
Is it even worth doing a new one?

903
00:42:50,924 --> 00:42:53,245
And if you take game design versus business strategy,

904
00:42:53,245 --> 00:42:55,865
because it's basically the same thing.

905
00:42:55,865 --> 00:42:58,145
Typically, when you run into a problem with a product,

906
00:42:58,145 --> 00:43:01,786
it has a business side and it has a development side.

907
00:43:01,786 --> 00:43:03,126
It's not opposite.

908
00:43:03,126 --> 00:43:04,287
It's actually the same.

909
00:43:04,287 --> 00:43:06,647
So we take the Crusader Kings 2 example.

910
00:43:06,647 --> 00:43:10,428
We have developer problems and we have business problems.

911
00:43:10,428 --> 00:43:15,229
The problem with previous versions of Crusader Kings

912
00:43:15,229 --> 00:43:18,829
was that every time we released something for it,

913
00:43:18,829 --> 00:43:20,690
it was different versions for different gamers.

914
00:43:22,261 --> 00:43:25,542
Which, on the other hand, on the business side,

915
00:43:25,542 --> 00:43:27,723
caused lower attachment rates for DLCs

916
00:43:27,723 --> 00:43:32,105
because you needed all the time to upgrade your game.

917
00:43:32,105 --> 00:43:36,087
The developer problem as well, this is actually Europa.

918
00:43:36,087 --> 00:43:39,349
Europa Universalis 3 was a game released before Crusader Kings

919
00:43:39,349 --> 00:43:41,110
2, so all the problems come from Europa 3.

920
00:43:41,951 --> 00:43:44,957
The multiplayer support, because you have different versions,

921
00:43:44,957 --> 00:43:47,162
you couldn't have multiplayer support in a good way,

922
00:43:47,162 --> 00:43:49,146
which made the business problem that customers

923
00:43:49,146 --> 00:43:51,331
weren't satisfied because it was not

924
00:43:51,331 --> 00:43:53,275
a full and complete product in the eyes of people.

925
00:43:56,795 --> 00:44:03,600
The developer problem also, which stemmed from different versions, was that it was problems to adapt the mods to all the different versions,

926
00:44:03,600 --> 00:44:07,764
which made the business problem that you had lower engagement rates on the people there,

927
00:44:07,764 --> 00:44:13,808
because they knew that maybe I can't download this mod because I have the wrong version and whatever, I don't really care.

928
00:44:13,808 --> 00:44:19,733
So, our solution to that was actually, every time we release a DLC,

929
00:44:21,539 --> 00:44:25,200
You download the whole game, and you get 50% of it for free,

930
00:44:25,200 --> 00:44:26,381
and the rest you unlock.

931
00:44:26,381 --> 00:44:29,423
But all the content is in there, so everyone is basically

932
00:44:29,423 --> 00:44:31,204
playing the same version.

933
00:44:31,204 --> 00:44:35,866
So what seems like a really simple solution actually

934
00:44:35,866 --> 00:44:38,567
took a lot of thinking, because both these things

935
00:44:38,567 --> 00:44:40,248
had to match in together.

936
00:44:40,248 --> 00:44:42,649
If this was only something that would

937
00:44:42,649 --> 00:44:44,630
have been solved from a development standpoint,

938
00:44:44,630 --> 00:44:46,712
I'm not sure that we would actually sort out

939
00:44:46,712 --> 00:44:47,832
the business problems.

940
00:44:49,023 --> 00:44:51,804
We could have found something completely different that

941
00:44:51,804 --> 00:44:54,486
took care of the developer problem,

942
00:44:54,486 --> 00:44:58,007
but what didn't make sense business-wise.

943
00:44:58,007 --> 00:44:59,828
Which takes me to the final part, which

944
00:44:59,828 --> 00:45:02,990
is the value creation part.

945
00:45:02,990 --> 00:45:05,611
And we have coined an expression that we call games

946
00:45:05,611 --> 00:45:07,532
as a platform on the value creation side.

947
00:45:07,532 --> 00:45:13,115
And value creation-wise is a gaming ecosystem

948
00:45:13,115 --> 00:45:15,776
created by you that continues to grow

949
00:45:15,776 --> 00:45:17,597
without your own involvement.

950
00:45:18,205 --> 00:45:20,947
So basically, it's a self-serving system of gamers.

951
00:45:20,947 --> 00:45:26,092
Team Fortress 2 is the best example in the world of this.

952
00:45:26,092 --> 00:45:29,696
So when you talk about value creation,

953
00:45:29,696 --> 00:45:32,478
like, who is actually creating value in this process?

954
00:45:32,478 --> 00:45:37,643
And what are the two key rules

955
00:45:37,643 --> 00:45:39,825
for how you make it possible for people

956
00:45:39,825 --> 00:45:41,107
to create value for your game?

957
00:45:42,982 --> 00:45:46,263
First one is, if you make it easy for people to create

958
00:45:46,263 --> 00:45:49,423
value, for example, mods, you're on the winning side of

959
00:45:49,423 --> 00:45:50,284
the games industry.

960
00:45:50,284 --> 00:45:54,945
If you make it hard, if you lock people out, you're on the

961
00:45:54,945 --> 00:45:57,766
losing side.

962
00:45:57,766 --> 00:46:03,428
If watching a YouTube video of your game adds value to the

963
00:46:03,428 --> 00:46:07,469
gamer rather than spoils the whole game, you're on the

964
00:46:07,469 --> 00:46:08,289
winning side of gaming.

965
00:46:09,506 --> 00:46:12,888
Those are the two golden rules of value creation

966
00:46:12,888 --> 00:46:20,312
and how your game is created and how it affects your game design.

967
00:46:20,312 --> 00:46:22,033
So it's not only about creating the value

968
00:46:22,033 --> 00:46:26,796
and how do you actually attract the people who create the value.

969
00:46:26,796 --> 00:46:27,336
Simple.

970
00:46:27,336 --> 00:46:32,599
First, lots of replayability, a lot of good mod support,

971
00:46:32,599 --> 00:46:34,080
dedicated people who take care of that.

972
00:46:34,567 --> 00:46:39,694
a YouTube friendliness. We talk a lot about what's the YouTube moment of this game.

